# Prevent Unnecessary Re-renders in React

You have several options depending on your situation:

## 1. **React.memo** (Functional Components)
Wraps your component to skip re-renders when props haven't changed:

```jsx
const MyComponent = React.memo(({ name, age }) => {
  return <div>{name} - {age}</div>;
});
```

**For custom comparison:**
```jsx
const MyComponent = React.memo(
  ({ name, age }) => <div>{name} - {age}</div>,
  (prevProps, nextProps) => {
    return prevProps.name === nextProps.name; // true = skip render
  }
);
```

## 2. **useMemo** (Memoize values)
Prevents child components from re-rendering due to new object references:

```jsx
function Parent() {
  const memoizedValue = useMemo(() => ({ id: 1 }), []);

  return <Child data={memoizedValue} />;
}
```

## 3. **useCallback** (Memoize functions)
Keeps function reference stable so child components don't re-render:

```jsx
function Parent() {
  const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
    console.log('clicked');
  }, []); // empty deps = function never changes

  return <Child onClick={handleClick} />;
}
```

## 4. **PureComponent** (Class Components)
Automatic shallow prop/state comparison:

```jsx
class MyComponent extends React.PureComponent {
  render() {
    return <div>{this.props.name}</div>;
  }
}
```

## Best Practices

✅ **Use React.memo for leaf components** (components that don't have many children)

✅ **Memoize callbacks/values** passed to memoized children

✅ **Keep dependencies arrays accurate** in useCallback/useMemo

⚠️ **Don't over-optimize** — profile first with React DevTools to find real bottlenecks

