# Streaming with Tool Use: A Practical Guide

Great question — this is a common point of confusion. Let me break down how streaming works with tools and show you the practical implementation.

## How Streaming Works with Tools

When you enable `stream: true`, Claude streams **content blocks progressively** as they're generated. Here's the key insight:

**Tool calls stream differently than text:**
- **Text blocks**: Stream character-by-character in real-time (you see "thinking" appear live)
- **Tool call blocks**: Stream parameter-by-parameter via **fine-grained tool streaming** (GA — no header needed)

The flow looks like:
```
User message
    ↓
Stream starts → [message_start] → [content_block_start] → [content_block_delta] ... → [content_block_stop]
                                                                ↑
                                        Tool call params build up here in deltas
    ↓
Tool call complete → You execute tool → Stream resumes with assistant's next message
```

## Implementation Pattern

Here's a complete example with web search and code execution:

```typescript
import Anthropic from "@anthropic-ai/sdk";

const client = new Anthropic();

async function streamWithTools(userMessage: string) {
  // Track accumulated state as stream progresses
  let currentToolCall: {
    id: string;
    name: string;
    input: Record<string, unknown>;
  } | null = null;
  let accumulatedInput = "";

  const toolUseStream = await client.messages.stream({
    model: "claude-opus-4-6",
    max_tokens: 4096,
    tools: [
      {
        type: "builtin_tool",
        name: "web_search",
      },
      {
        type: "builtin_tool",
        name: "code_execution",
      },
    ],
    messages: [
      {
        role: "user",
        content: userMessage,
      },
    ],
  });

  // Process stream events
  for await (const event of toolUseStream) {
    switch (event.type) {
      case "content_block_start":
        if (event.content_block.type === "tool_use") {
          currentToolCall = {
            id: event.content_block.id,
            name: event.content_block.name,
            input: {},
          };
          accumulatedInput = "";
          console.log(`\n🔧 Tool: ${event.content_block.name}`);
        } else if (event.content_block.type === "text") {
          console.log("\n💭 ", "");
        }
        break;

      case "content_block_delta":
        if (event.delta.type === "text_delta") {
          // Stream text in real-time
          process.stdout.write(event.delta.text);
        } else if (event.delta.type === "input_json_delta") {
          // Accumulate tool input JSON as it streams
          accumulatedInput += event.delta.partial_json;
          console.log(`  Params: ${accumulatedInput}`);
        }
        break;

      case "content_block_stop":
        if (currentToolCall) {
          // Parse complete tool input
          currentToolCall.input = JSON.parse(accumulatedInput);
          console.log(
            `  ✓ Ready to execute: ${JSON.stringify(currentToolCall.input)}`
          );
        }
        break;

      case "message_stop":
        console.log("\n✅ Stream complete");
        break;
    }
  }

  // Get final message with tool results
  const finalMessage = await toolUseStream.finalMessage();
  return finalMessage;
}

// Usage
streamWithTools(
  "Search for latest Claude updates and show me a code example"
);
```

## Real-Time vs Tool Execution Trade-off

Here's the crucial decision point:

### Option 1: Stream Everything, Then Execute Tools (Simpler)
```typescript
// Wait for stream to complete, THEN handle tool calls
const message = await streamWithTools(userMessage);

// Now inspect message.content for tool_use blocks
const toolCalls = message.content.filter((c) => c.type === "tool_use");
for (const toolCall of toolCalls) {
  const result = await executeTool(toolCall);
  // Continue conversation with tool result
}
```

**Pros:**
- Simpler to implement
- See Claude's reasoning stream live
- Clear execution order

**Cons:**
- Tool execution doesn't start until stream finishes
- Overall latency = streaming time + tool execution time

### Option 2: Execute Tools Immediately (Lower Latency)
```typescript
async function streamWithImmediateToolExecution(userMessage: string) {
  const toolResults: Array<{
    type: "tool_result";
    tool_use_id: string;
    content: string;
  }> = [];

  // First stream
  const initialStream = await client.messages.stream({
    model: "claude-opus-4-6",
    max_tokens: 4096,
    tools: [
      { type: "builtin_tool", name: "web_search" },
      { type: "builtin_tool", name: "code_execution" },
    ],
    messages: [{ role: "user", content: userMessage }],
  });

  const firstMessage = await initialStream.finalMessage();

  // Execute any tool calls immediately
  for (const content of firstMessage.content) {
    if (content.type === "tool_use") {
      console.log(`🔧 Executing ${content.name}...`);
      const result = await executeTool(content.name, content.input);
      console.log(`✓ Result: ${result}`);

      toolResults.push({
        type: "tool_result",
        tool_use_id: content.id,
        content: result,
      });
    }
  }

  // Continue conversation with results (stream this too)
  if (toolResults.length > 0) {
    const messages = [
      { role: "user", content: userMessage },
      { role: "assistant", content: firstMessage.content },
      { role: "user", content: toolResults },
    ];

    const finalStream = await client.messages.stream({
      model: "claude-opus-4-6",
      max_tokens: 4096,
      tools: [{ type: "builtin_tool", name: "web_search" }],
      messages,
    });

    for await (const event of finalStream) {
      if (event.type === "content_block_delta" && event.delta.type === "text_delta") {
        process.stdout.write(event.delta.text);
      }
    }
  }
}
```

**Pros:**
- Tools execute in parallel with Claude's reasoning on next message
- Better end-to-end latency for multi-step workflows

**Cons:**
- More complex state management
- Tool result formatting must match expectations

## Handling Web Search + Code Execution Together

When Claude calls both tools in sequence:

```typescript
async function executeTool(
  name: string,
  input: Record<string, unknown>
): Promise<string> {
  if (name === "web_search") {
    // Execute search (built-in, but you'd wrap an API call)
    console.log(`Searching: ${input.query}`);
    return `Search results for "${input.query}"...`;
  } else if (name === "code_execution") {
    // Execute code
    console.log(`Running code:\n${input.code}`);
    // In production, use a sandbox
    return `Code executed successfully`;
  }
  return "Unknown tool";
}
```

## Key Gotchas

| Issue | Solution |
|-------|----------|
| Tool params incomplete | Don't process until `content_block_stop` event |
| Tool execution blocks UI | Use Option 2 (immediate execution) or offload to background |
| Can't see Claude's reasoning | Use `thinking: {type: "adaptive"}` to stream thoughts too |
| Tool result truncation | Summarize large results; Claude handles up to 4 messages of context |
| Nested tool calls | Claude makes all calls in one response; handle them all before next turn |

